can variant spelling of   St  .   Claire  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Claire","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Clare  .","Variant of   Clair  , an altered form of German   Klare  .","French: variant of   Clair  ."]},{"name":"St","meanings":["Americanized spelling of French   St  .   Denis  ."]}]},{"name":"Liz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Galician: habitational name from Liz in Lugo province, Galicia (Spain). As a Hispanic name it may also be an altered form of   Lis  . Compare   Deliz  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Stanislaw, Wladyslaw, Andrzej, Casimir, Ignatius, Malgorzata, Slawomir, Tadeusz, Tomasz, Boleslaw, Bronislaw, Darek.","Polish, Czech, Sorbian, and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): from Polish and Czech dialect <i>lis</i> ‘fox’, Upper Sorbian <i>lis</i> ‘he-fox’, a nickname for a cunning person or, in the case of the Jewish name, an artificial name. The presumably cognate Sorbian surname <b>Liš</b> is found in Germanized and probably also Americanized forms, only (see   Liesch   and   Lish  ). Compare also   Lese  ,   Lies  , and   Liss  .","Czech: nickname for a man with a bald pate, from a variant of the adjective <i>lysý</i> ‘bald’."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":105,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":114,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Emma de St. Liz was born in 1110, in Northamptonshire, England as the daughter of Hugh de Senlis and Hawise Ridel. She had at least 1 daughter with Ivo de Braybrooke. She died in Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, England."},"et":{"1110–":"1110–Surnud","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","1092–1146":"1092–1146","1120–1168":"1120–1168","1093–1110":"1093–1110","–1114":"–1114","Abt 1120":"umbes 1120","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1114":"1114","1168":"1168","1146":"1146","1110":"1110","1120":"1120","1093":"1093","1092":"1092","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, England":"Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1110–":"1110–Kuollut","1110–Female":"1110–Kuollut","1092–1146":"1092–1146","1120–1168":"1120–1168","1093–1110":"1093–1110","–1114":"–1114","Abt 1120":"noin 1120","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1114":"1114","1168":"1168","1146":"1146","1110":"1110","1120":"1120","1093":"1093","1092":"1092","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, England":"Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, England"},